We held our company's largest luncheon/happy of the year at Old Crow's Atrium/Tunnel. Everything was perfect and went seamlessly. The food was plentiful and received many compliments, the staff were attentive and accommodating to meet all of our requests, and all of our guests seemed to have a wonderful time. Additionally, the roof was retracted for our group, which made for a very refreshing and beautiful atmosphere. From the planning phase to the day of the event, Old Crow's Event Managers made sure to take note our group's needs, customize the venue and menu to our specifications, and deliver on their promises. I would gladly use the venue in the future for another corporate event or for a large gathering. 10/10 - would recommend!

We had Marissa as a waitress. I believe there was around 4 full tables as we got there. Pretty empty besides that. I read through the menu, waited for a waitress/waiter, but no one came. I then went to the bar thinking they might serve us if there’s not waiter or waitress around. He said he’d grab a waitress. We got Marissa. She was fine at first, normal “how are you doing” ready to go we ordered drink and said we were ready for food too. My two friends ordered and then I went. I asked for a pulled pork and then asked if they had sweet potato fries. Marissa asked “well did you read the menu? If you did you’d... never mind I’m busy” and she walked away.  Later I asked her “I’m sorry, but have you never answered a question as a waitress?” She looked away and said “yeah well I need to go, I’m busy”  She ignored our table for the remainder of the night. We were there for 2 hours and she served us one drink. We had to go up to the bar after that. She finally gave us a check and we tipped her lower than I ever have, 5%.  At first, I felt bad since I’m sure she was just stressed out and had a tough day, that was until she walked over to her manager and next thing I knew her manager walked over to us.  He then kicked us out for not tipping. I told him the story and he just said “she’s our best server and we’ve never heard that before and you need to leave” told him I’ve been at their frequently and he said “oh well it’s your friend who’s drunk” who had three drinks all night. It was a very lame excuse to keep your server happy...  I am honestly just upset their server ended up being in the wrong and got her way regarding sweat potato fries...

I only knew of country bars through the film's of Clint Eastwood and John Wayne. The kind of places you call Saloons, where it's dirty, guys are playing crooked poker, a man on an instrument called the "peeanny", and bar fights galore!  Old Crow Smokehouse is far from any of those things. It's a solid place where you can drink out of a clean Mason jar and not have to worry about an ornery varmint threatening you to a quick draw. A place that serves delicious USDA barbeque meats, legit kinds! Not those questionable vittles that Cookie has in the chuck wagon.  The wait staff is very friendly and won't spit in your drink. Although I will say they won't just sell you a whole bottle of whiskey to drown out your sorrows for your failed gold prospecting. They will hand you a pretty decent beer list that will meet anyone's basic taste for sasaparilla.  It's like West World, only more family friendly. And this bar really likes those city slicking Steelers.

Our staff came here for a catered dinner in a private area. There were A LOT of us (2 charter busses), and even though the details were discussed ahead of time, Old Crow was not prepared for the event. There was only enough seating for about 1/4th of us, and we had to stand around waiting for more tables to be set up. The food was served buffet style, and the containers were not refilled promptly, so that meant more standing around waiting for food. On top of everything the food was only so so. The reason I didn't rate them one star was because the place had a cool vibe. I could imagine going there to watch a game or something.
